WEBVTT

01:02.830 --> 01:04.798
Hello, everybody.

01:04.865 --> 01:06.834
How are you

01:06.900 --> 01:09.537
Thank you. Good to see you.
Thank you for coming.

01:15.643 --> 01:17.778
Cold out there!

01:17.845 --> 01:19.213
That is cold.

01:20.214 --> 01:22.283
Hello, everybody!

01:23.784 --> 01:25.386
Hello!

01:25.453 --> 01:30.057
Hello. Welcome to The Grand
Tour. Happy Christmas.

01:30.158 --> 01:31.692
This week, we are coming -

01:31.759 --> 01:35.229
if you can see through
the drizzle dribbling down
the windows -

01:35.296 --> 01:36.664
from Scandinavia.

01:39.533 --> 01:40.868
Oh, yeah.

01:40.934 --> 01:42.236
This, of course...

01:42.303 --> 01:45.639
This, of course, is the home
of those gloomy dramas

01:45.706 --> 01:48.642
where a weird woman
in a jumper solves a murder

01:48.709 --> 01:51.579
by staring at a lake
for six hours.

01:52.846 --> 01:54.848
This will probably be
the jolliest programme

01:54.915 --> 01:57.218
to come out of this
neck of the woods since...

01:57.285 --> 01:58.619
... Four Funerals
And A Funeral .

01:58.686 --> 02:00.020
JEREMY: Yeah.

02:00.188 --> 02:02.423
Swedish rom-com that was.
Erm...

02:02.490 --> 02:04.325
When Harry Shot Sally .

02:04.392 --> 02:05.693
Oh, a laugh a minute.

02:05.759 --> 02:08.196
The Girl With
The Pearl Necklace. No.

02:09.697 --> 02:12.800
-That's another sort of
Scandinavian film.

02:12.866 --> 02:14.268
Yeah.

02:17.037 --> 02:18.306
Anyway, specifically,

02:18.372 --> 02:22.075
we are deep inside
the Arctic Circle in Finland.

02:24.312 --> 02:27.481
There you go.
And Finland, of course...

02:27.548 --> 02:33.354
Finland, of course, is home
to every single racing driver
currently...

02:36.324 --> 02:39.092
Well, apart from
Nico Rosberg, who is Finnish,

02:39.227 --> 02:41.529
but, for some reason,
claims he's German.

02:43.664 --> 02:46.234
Why does he do that?
I have no idea.

02:46.300 --> 02:47.468
Who else is there, then?

02:47.535 --> 02:48.736
Well, there's Mika Salo,

02:48.802 --> 02:50.538
Mika Häkkinen,
Kimi Räikkönen.

02:50.604 --> 02:53.274
Hang on, they're just
anagrams of the same name,
aren't they?

02:53.341 --> 02:55.276
-Then you've got rallying.

02:55.343 --> 02:57.611
There's Tommi Mäkinen,
Timo Mäkinen,

02:57.678 --> 03:00.080
Juha Kankkunen, Ari Vatanen.

03:00.248 --> 03:01.649
More anagrams.

03:02.916 --> 03:04.618
Kinky Wankinen.

03:07.288 --> 03:08.956
Manky Pantiden.

03:09.022 --> 03:10.591
Really?

03:10.658 --> 03:12.760
I'm getting
slightly carried away now.

03:12.826 --> 03:15.028
Seriously, I went on
Wikipedia last night

03:15.095 --> 03:18.266
to look for famous Finns
who aren't racing drivers.

03:18.299 --> 03:19.600
Put up the list I found.

03:19.667 --> 03:22.336
And I noticed something -
they're all men.

03:22.403 --> 03:24.372
-All of them.

03:24.438 --> 03:26.674
Are there any famous
Finnish women?

03:30.478 --> 03:33.314
Nobody thinks so.
They're all...

03:33.381 --> 03:34.648
I know why, OK?

03:34.715 --> 03:38.352
It's because all Finnish
women, at the age of 19,

03:38.419 --> 03:40.020
move to England
to be au pairs.

03:41.822 --> 03:44.658
I actually had three Finnish
au pairs over the years
for my children.

03:44.725 --> 03:46.427
-Yeah. It was always funny.

03:46.494 --> 03:49.096
You'd go to Heathrow airport
to pick up your new au pair,

03:49.162 --> 03:53.200
and there'd always be a row
of 30-something fathers
waiting at the gate

03:53.301 --> 03:56.337
for their Scandinavian
au pair to come out.

03:57.771 --> 03:59.807
And there was one year
I've never forgotten.

03:59.873 --> 04:03.511
This huge moose
lumbered out of the door,

04:03.577 --> 04:08.048
and the man next to me looked
at his piece of paper and
went, "Oh, for God's sake!"

04:11.151 --> 04:12.353
That's not good.

04:16.724 --> 04:18.959
-Shall we get on with
the show?
-Yes, good idea.

04:19.026 --> 04:23.464
Because tonight
in our television
programme about cars...

04:23.531 --> 04:25.433
I eat some cheddar.

04:27.501 --> 04:29.937
Richard says
he doesn't want any.

04:30.003 --> 04:32.039
I don't want cheese.

04:32.105 --> 04:37.611
And James compares
a Ford GT40 to a Ferrari P3.

04:37.678 --> 04:40.180
Avanti!

04:40.247 --> 04:43.050
But first, if you are
watching this in America,

04:43.116 --> 04:44.818
you may be amazed to hear

04:44.885 --> 04:50.023
that the Ford Mustang
has never been sold,
officially, in the UK.

04:50.090 --> 04:52.760
Well, until now,
because Ford has now decided

04:52.826 --> 04:55.863
that the latest Mustang
will be sold in the UK

04:55.929 --> 04:59.032
with a V8 engine
and right-hand drive.

04:59.099 --> 05:03.471
Mm, and this has made
our other resident American
very happy.

05:03.537 --> 05:05.573
He was so excited, in fact,

05:05.639 --> 05:08.275
that when the first
right-hand-drive Mustang

05:08.376 --> 05:10.277
arrived at the docks
in the UK,

05:10.378 --> 05:12.680
he was actually there
to meet it.

05:34.468 --> 05:36.404
It'll be here any minute.

05:47.815 --> 05:50.317
That is it. Are we ready?

05:50.418 --> 05:53.821
This is the moment.
It's touched down!

05:53.887 --> 05:54.822
Go, go, go!

05:54.888 --> 05:56.957
* New World Symphony

06:02.463 --> 06:05.165
Look, it's a bit gloomy,
isn't it?

06:05.232 --> 06:08.769
It's not very welcoming.
Have you got anything
more upbeat?

06:08.836 --> 06:12.606
* When The Saints
Go Marching In

06:12.673 --> 06:14.442
Forget it!
Forget it! Forget it!

06:14.508 --> 06:16.577
-Forget it.

06:21.048 --> 06:23.584
I'm so excited,
my tinkle is fizzing.

06:30.891 --> 06:31.759
Oh, yeah!

06:31.825 --> 06:33.927
* National Anthem of USSR

06:37.798 --> 06:39.833
Oh. Sorry about that.

06:39.900 --> 06:41.935
We really are useless
over here.

06:42.002 --> 06:44.972
It's one of the reasons we
needed your help in the war.

06:48.308 --> 06:49.877
I decided that, first of all,

06:49.943 --> 06:52.179
I'd show
the new Mustang around,

06:52.245 --> 06:54.515
so I headed for London...

06:54.582 --> 06:56.116
which is the capital city.

07:15.969 --> 07:18.672
Ah, now,
this is Tower Bridge.

07:18.739 --> 07:21.742
Interesting.
It's very, very old.

07:21.809 --> 07:24.077
But it folds
completely in half

07:24.144 --> 07:27.047
so that, in the old days,
the horses could go through.

07:30.684 --> 07:33.253
Now, that's
the Houses of Parliament,

07:33.320 --> 07:36.757
which are a series of houses
in which we keep
all our idiots.

07:36.824 --> 07:40.427
That clock thing,
that's Big Ben.

07:40.528 --> 07:44.632
I know it's not what you call
big, but... but we couldn't
just call it Ben.

07:46.634 --> 07:49.302
And that is the Cenotaph,

07:49.369 --> 07:53.106
where we remember those
who died fighting for us.

07:54.441 --> 07:56.544
Slowing down a bit here.

07:56.610 --> 07:57.945
Show some respect.

08:00.881 --> 08:03.751
No idea what that is.
It wasn't here this morning.

08:06.019 --> 08:08.355
A cyclist, you want to be
careful of those.

08:08.421 --> 08:10.691
Small
but very angry creatures.

08:13.193 --> 08:15.262
That's the army.

08:15.328 --> 08:17.598
They're the ones
who shot at your White House.

08:17.665 --> 08:18.899
Sorry about that.

08:20.067 --> 08:22.636
Having seen
all of the sights,

08:22.703 --> 08:24.738
we headed out of town

08:24.805 --> 08:26.574
so I could do this.

08:31.078 --> 08:32.580
There it is.

08:32.580 --> 08:36.817
That is the soundtrack
that Britain has been missing
for 51 years -

08:36.884 --> 08:39.219
real American V8 muscle.

08:43.290 --> 08:46.960
We just don't make cars like
this on our side of the pond.

08:47.027 --> 08:50.798
All that
lazy-but-determined torque.

08:50.864 --> 08:54.802
Squeeze the throttle
in any gear at any speed...

08:54.868 --> 08:57.337
...and there's
an inevitability
to the way it moves off.

08:57.404 --> 09:00.608
It's like arm wrestling
a solar system -
you're gonna lose.

09:11.251 --> 09:12.820
It is weird...

09:12.886 --> 09:15.923
driving a Mustang
from this side.

09:15.989 --> 09:17.691
It's like suddenly
changing your mind

09:17.758 --> 09:20.794
after 50 years of marriage
and sleeping on the other
side of the bed.

09:22.763 --> 09:25.132
It's also weird
driving a car with a big V8,

09:25.198 --> 09:27.267
reversing camera,
air-conditioned seats,

09:27.334 --> 09:32.105
rain-sensing wipers
that you can buy for £37,000.

09:32.172 --> 09:35.643
That's half of what you'd pay
for a BMW M4. Half.

09:38.912 --> 09:41.081
Once we were in
the countryside proper,

09:41.148 --> 09:43.651
I continued
my sightseeing tour.

09:45.085 --> 09:47.855
Look, I've drawn your badge
on a hill.

09:54.962 --> 09:56.163
Jeremy did that one.

10:00.000 --> 10:01.735
Sorry.

10:04.137 --> 10:07.074
Eventually,
we arrived at Stonehenge.

10:09.576 --> 10:12.345
That,
you'll be amazed to learn,

10:12.412 --> 10:14.381
is an ancient calendar.

10:16.216 --> 10:18.418
Or a clock. Or a church.

10:18.485 --> 10:23.156
My tour of Britain
was then interrupted
by an unwelcome arrival.

10:25.425 --> 10:26.660
What are you doing here?

10:26.727 --> 10:29.562
Well,
I have come to remind you -

10:29.629 --> 10:31.398
cos you've obviously
forgotten,

10:31.464 --> 10:32.866
cos you're too giddy -

10:32.933 --> 10:36.003
that we have no need
for the Mustang in Britain.

10:36.069 --> 10:38.171
Because if you want to spend,

10:38.238 --> 10:41.341
what, £30,000-£35,000
on a fast Ford,

10:41.408 --> 10:44.878
you'd buy a Focus RS, cos
that was designed for here.

10:44.945 --> 10:47.514
No, you'd settle for that
in the UK

10:47.580 --> 10:50.317
because you couldn't
buy this, but now you can.

10:50.383 --> 10:51.719
That is the point.

10:51.785 --> 10:53.721
Would you wear chaps?

10:53.787 --> 10:55.923
No, because we have trousers.

10:55.989 --> 10:57.958
What about cowboy...
Oh, you are. Cowboy boots.

10:58.025 --> 10:59.693
Well, it's appropriate.
I'm welcoming...

10:59.760 --> 11:03.363
Listen, I don't want
everything from America,
I just want the Mustang.

11:03.430 --> 11:04.597
-Stupid.
-No, America--

11:04.732 --> 11:06.266
It wasn't designed for here.

11:06.333 --> 11:08.736
-Well, no.

11:08.736 --> 11:10.738
"It's cold out,
I'll wear a Stetson."

11:10.738 --> 11:12.639
No! You wear a bobble hat.

11:12.740 --> 11:14.374
That's a bobble hat.

11:14.441 --> 11:16.276
Oh! No, hang on.

11:17.811 --> 11:19.412
-I've just realised.

11:19.479 --> 11:22.015
Erm... I-I don't want
to talk to you any more.

11:40.200 --> 11:41.769
Anyway...

11:41.835 --> 11:45.405
Anyway, we shall
pick that up later on.

11:45.472 --> 11:47.975
But right now
it's time to drop it a cog

11:48.041 --> 11:51.779
and hook a left
into Conversation Street.

12:00.520 --> 12:03.791
-Serious. It's serious.
-It is serious stuff, this.

12:05.125 --> 12:07.360
Now, look, in Britain
we are always being told

12:07.427 --> 12:09.830
that the Scandinavians
are brilliant at driving,

12:09.897 --> 12:13.666
and that's because they would
be, because they have
to deal with all that snow.

12:13.801 --> 12:17.805
Mm, they're brilliant
because what they do
most of all is crash.

12:17.871 --> 12:19.672
Well, you're absolutely
right, as it turns out,

12:19.807 --> 12:22.542
cos I've got some interesting
statistics here. Erm...

12:22.609 --> 12:27.114
In Britain, 1.2% of accidents
result in fatalities.

12:27.180 --> 12:29.817
Here, I'm afraid, it's 5.1%.

12:29.883 --> 12:31.819
Yeah, and it's not just
the Finns, either,

12:31.819 --> 12:33.821
if I may be so bold.

12:33.821 --> 12:36.289
Our Senior
International Producer -

12:36.356 --> 12:37.825
that's his job title -

12:37.858 --> 12:39.592
came over to Finland
the other day,

12:39.659 --> 12:41.728
rented himself a BMW
at the airport -

12:41.829 --> 12:44.064
not a Ford or an Opel,
you'll note, a BMW -

12:44.131 --> 12:46.366
and on his way to
the location here,

12:46.433 --> 12:47.700
this happened.

12:47.835 --> 12:49.903
RICHARD: He did! He did!

12:49.970 --> 12:52.272
When I say he's our Senior
International Producer,

12:52.339 --> 12:54.842
he's now our Junior
International Producer.

12:54.875 --> 12:57.477
-Our Junior Local Producer.
-Yeah.

12:57.544 --> 13:00.247
Very local. Specifically,
the stationery cupboard.

13:00.313 --> 13:02.883
-He can produce that.
-That's all
he's in charge of.

13:02.950 --> 13:04.852
How did he do that?!

13:04.852 --> 13:08.255
The thing is, what I don't
understand is how the Finns
manage to go fast enough

13:08.321 --> 13:10.323
to have a crash
of any sort at all,

13:10.390 --> 13:13.593
because the speeding fines
here are insane.

13:13.660 --> 13:15.662
They're means tested,

13:15.728 --> 13:17.530
which means
a guy here recently

13:17.597 --> 13:20.267
was caught doing 49mph
through a 30 zone

13:20.333 --> 13:25.105
and he was fined
112,000 euros.

13:25.172 --> 13:27.040
-That's a speeding fine!

13:27.107 --> 13:29.009
Are they really that high
in Finland?

13:31.044 --> 13:32.345
A hundred and twelve...

13:32.412 --> 13:33.746
112,000.

13:33.881 --> 13:36.483
-Imagine getting that
in the post!
-Well, it's interesting.

13:36.549 --> 13:39.419
Actually, there was
a Finnish minister
recently said

13:39.486 --> 13:42.189
that the government
needs those speeding fines

13:42.255 --> 13:44.524
to balance the books,
they said.

13:44.591 --> 13:47.995
They actually said, "Speeding
is good for the country."

13:48.061 --> 13:50.363
-That is actually what...

13:50.430 --> 13:52.165
JEREMY:
Because it is. Every country.

13:52.232 --> 13:55.402
RICHARD:
Right. We should adopt that.

13:55.468 --> 13:58.271
-Speeding is good for you.
-It's your social duty.

13:58.338 --> 14:00.507
-A bit more conversation
for you.
-Oh, good!

14:02.142 --> 14:04.677
I think, with the exception
of Rolls-Royce,

14:04.744 --> 14:08.748
Volvo now make the best
car interiors of anybody.

14:10.350 --> 14:12.385
They do.
They're very, very good.

14:12.452 --> 14:14.421
I don't like to,
but I agree with you.

14:14.487 --> 14:18.158
because I went in the new S90
the other day,
and the interior is superb.

14:18.225 --> 14:20.693
-We've got
a picture of it here.
-Yes, that one.

14:20.760 --> 14:22.395
JEREMY:
They use pale colours.

14:22.462 --> 14:24.497
They've got pale-coloured
seats, pale-coloured carpets,
pale wood,

14:24.564 --> 14:27.400
and that makes it feel light
and airy and spacious.

14:27.467 --> 14:30.137
The only problem is
that in one of those

14:30.203 --> 14:33.473
you couldn't enjoy
a chocolate Magnum ice cream.

14:34.541 --> 14:36.576
It's all right,
I don't eat ice cream.

14:36.643 --> 14:38.645
It's something to do with
being straight.

14:41.581 --> 14:42.950
What

14:42.983 --> 14:44.317
Why are you applauding him?

14:46.954 --> 14:48.088
What do you mean?

14:48.155 --> 14:50.457
Are you saying
everyone who likes ice...?

14:50.523 --> 14:52.625
Ice cream is a bit,
you know....

14:52.692 --> 14:55.028
You're saying all children
are homosexual?

14:55.095 --> 14:56.363
-No, but...

14:56.429 --> 14:58.165
There's nothing
wrong with it,

14:58.231 --> 15:01.101
but a grown man
eating an ice cream,
you know, it's a bit...

15:01.168 --> 15:02.835
it's that way
rather than that way.

15:02.970 --> 15:04.171
-It is...

15:04.237 --> 15:07.007
Welcome to the inside of
Richard Hammond's head.

15:07.074 --> 15:09.109
I'm right. I can't believe
you can't see that.

15:09.176 --> 15:10.510
It's easy.
It's in front of you.

15:10.577 --> 15:13.480
You could enjoy a 99
in there.

15:13.546 --> 15:15.415
-No...

15:15.482 --> 15:18.151
Ninety-nine. But you couldn't
have the chocolate thingy.

15:18.218 --> 15:20.453
-My case rests!
-No, the chocolate thing!

15:20.520 --> 15:22.522
-Exactly!
-You know what I mean.

15:22.589 --> 15:24.992
No,
but if you had that Volvo,

15:25.058 --> 15:26.393
you could have
a white magnum...

15:26.459 --> 15:28.161
JEREMY: True.
-...or a Milky Bar.

15:28.228 --> 15:30.797
Yeah,
but not a Double Decker.

15:30.863 --> 15:32.199
Well, a Flake is worse.

15:32.265 --> 15:34.334
-No, Double Decker's worse.

15:34.401 --> 15:35.535
Double Decker...

15:35.602 --> 15:37.704
Do you all know what I mean
by the Double Decker?

15:37.770 --> 15:40.873
It is unique among chocolate
confectionery items.

15:41.008 --> 15:42.775
Take a bite
as you're driving along,

15:42.842 --> 15:45.012
and a bit about this big, OK,

15:45.078 --> 15:46.646
silently breaks away...

15:47.914 --> 15:49.916
...goes down
between your legs

15:50.017 --> 15:51.751
and melts.

15:51.818 --> 15:53.286
So when you get out,

15:53.353 --> 15:56.123
everybody thinks
you've had some kind
of trouser accident.

15:56.189 --> 15:59.559
This big brown stain right...

15:59.626 --> 16:02.495
-I know what you mean.
-It does happen.

16:02.562 --> 16:04.131
A Flake is worse.

16:04.197 --> 16:05.798
No, it just isn't!

16:05.865 --> 16:08.635
A Flake is advertised
as "the crumbliest,
flakiest chocolate".

16:08.701 --> 16:11.504
-It is worse.
-This is a hot topic on
Conversation Street.

16:11.571 --> 16:12.539
It is!

16:12.605 --> 16:14.607
I think we should settle it
here and now.

16:14.674 --> 16:16.876
I'm going to go into
our travelling box.

16:20.747 --> 16:23.883
Our travelling box of
chocolate confectionery,
and I'm going to...

16:23.950 --> 16:25.852
Let's settle it
with a competition, yes?

16:25.918 --> 16:27.320
I'm gonna give you
James's Flake

16:27.387 --> 16:29.222
and you the Double Decker.

16:29.289 --> 16:33.493
I'll turn that over, so then
you'll see how much spills
off as I eat the Flake.

16:33.560 --> 16:35.562
-This is scientific.

16:36.729 --> 16:38.865
Here we go. Oh.
Some of it's already crum...

16:38.931 --> 16:41.368
This is cheating, this one.

16:41.434 --> 16:43.103
RICHARD: OK, no,
clear away the debris.

16:43.170 --> 16:45.072
JEREMY:
No, I need to... Jesus!

16:45.072 --> 16:48.475
-That's part of eating it!
-It isn't part of eating it!
I haven't even begun.

16:48.541 --> 16:50.477
-But you've got to unwrap it.
-Ssh!

16:50.543 --> 16:51.444
Cheat.

16:51.511 --> 16:53.980
* Only the crumbliest *

16:54.081 --> 16:55.682
* Flakiest chocolate *

16:55.748 --> 16:57.617
-Oh, God.
* Tastes like choc... *

16:57.684 --> 16:59.852
-Jeremy,
you know that advert?

16:59.919 --> 17:02.089
-Girl in...

17:02.122 --> 17:06.126
Girl in the the field
of poppies - we're not
seeing that right now.

17:06.193 --> 17:07.694
-I am.
-I'm not.

17:07.760 --> 17:08.995
Right, ready? Watch this.

17:09.096 --> 17:11.098
RICHARD:
He's going in. First bite.

17:11.098 --> 17:12.865
Oh, it's a big fall
of chocolate!

17:12.932 --> 17:15.135
JEREMY: Mm.
-It's a heavy sprinkling,
that.

17:15.202 --> 17:17.204
That is just a light dusting
of chocolate.

17:17.270 --> 17:19.106
-A light dusting, yeah, OK.
-Right, James May.

17:19.139 --> 17:23.810
Moving over to James May
and his Double Decker.
This is exciting, isn't it?

17:23.876 --> 17:27.314
-This is a great
car programme.
-Groundbreaking stuff, yeah.

17:27.380 --> 17:29.582
-Quiet, please.
-I can't believe...

17:29.649 --> 17:33.019
-I can't believe this hasn't
been done before.

17:33.120 --> 17:35.122
He's going in.
He's taking a bite.

17:36.756 --> 17:38.991
His poor old gnash...
His teeth!

17:39.126 --> 17:40.393
-Oh!

17:40.460 --> 17:44.297
It's a catastrophic fall!
The clear winner...

17:44.364 --> 17:48.768
The Double Decker
is worse than the Flake.

17:48.835 --> 17:51.804
There's the Flake.
There's the Double Decker.

17:51.871 --> 17:54.541
So, there we are.
Using science,
we have now established...

17:54.607 --> 17:57.977
...if you've got a Volvo,
don't have a Double Decker.

17:58.044 --> 17:59.312
-Ever.

17:59.379 --> 18:01.848
Or an ice cream, because
he... Oh, no, forget it.

18:01.914 --> 18:05.952
Let's move a little further
along Conversation Street,
shall we?

18:06.018 --> 18:07.820
Erm...
A few weeks ago, Amazon,

18:07.887 --> 18:11.158
they ran an advert
for our show, and we're
rather pleased with it.

18:11.191 --> 18:12.425
See, it's got everything in.

18:12.492 --> 18:14.627
-Yeah, the sense of travel.
-Logo.

18:14.694 --> 18:17.063
-And there's even the goat.
-Yeah, no, that's perfect.

18:17.164 --> 18:21.000
-Everything you need there.
-All you need for the advert.
It's on the screen.

18:22.702 --> 18:27.073
Yeah. All the essentials are
there. Everything you need.

18:27.174 --> 18:28.541
Everything you need to see.

18:30.677 --> 18:32.779
JEREMY: Actually...

18:32.845 --> 18:33.980
All the important stuff.

18:34.046 --> 18:35.648
Hammond,
I'm sorry to do this,

18:35.715 --> 18:38.651
but before the show launched,
Amazon did another advert,
OK,

18:38.718 --> 18:41.654
which somebody sent to me
on a tweet,
which I screen grabbed,

18:41.721 --> 18:44.591
so the quality's not good,
but I have brought it along.

18:44.657 --> 18:45.825
Here it is.

18:45.892 --> 18:46.926
Oh, for God's sake!

18:52.632 --> 18:56.436
I like their marketing
department a lot.

18:56.503 --> 18:58.271
I think that's enough
Conversation Street,

18:58.338 --> 18:59.872
so let's get back
to our film.

18:59.939 --> 19:03.276
Yes. Earlier on,
I was in the right-hand-drive
Ford Mustang,

19:03.343 --> 19:05.345
showing it the sights
around our country.

19:05.412 --> 19:07.214
Unfortunately, he turned up

19:07.214 --> 19:11.418
and tried to argue that
the similarly priced
Ford Focus was a better bet.

19:11.484 --> 19:17.224
-Yeah, I did do that.
-I responded by driving off
and refusing to talk to you.

19:17.257 --> 19:18.591
A bit rudely, I thought.

19:24.731 --> 19:27.834
I'm sorry, this is my film,
my tour of England,

19:27.900 --> 19:30.437
and I didn't want him
spoiling it.

19:34.941 --> 19:36.243
This thing's bloody awesome.

19:38.811 --> 19:39.812
Listen to that bellow.

19:39.879 --> 19:42.014
This thing squats
on its haunches.

19:42.081 --> 19:44.651
This is what
it's built to do.

19:44.717 --> 19:50.690
Every crackle, pop and bang
is just connected to every
synapse and sinew in me.

19:53.693 --> 19:55.262
Oh, no.

20:00.567 --> 20:03.703
This is like a first date
for me, and on a first date,

20:03.770 --> 20:07.607
you don't want a fat,
balding uncle tagging along.

20:09.276 --> 20:12.211
So what I'm gonna do now...
is lose him.

20:16.516 --> 20:19.218
It's Hammer Time!
Shock and awe!

20:26.593 --> 20:28.661
It's Bond versus Bourne.

20:36.436 --> 20:40.307
He's got five litres.
I've only got 2.3.

20:40.373 --> 20:43.410
Is he going twice as fast?
No, he is not.

20:48.815 --> 20:51.651
Corner coming up.
There's no need to panic
any more in a Mustang,

20:51.718 --> 20:53.586
because, for the first time,

20:53.653 --> 20:55.988
the Mustang has
independent rear suspension.

21:02.161 --> 21:03.496
Ooh!

21:05.498 --> 21:09.702
The cornering speeds
this thing can achieve...
beggar belief.

21:20.413 --> 21:22.715
How does it grip that well?!

21:26.919 --> 21:30.256
I'm in a car chase
in a Mustang.

21:30.357 --> 21:31.724
I am Steve McQueen.

21:37.764 --> 21:39.466
Try that on.

21:43.135 --> 21:44.471
I've got it in Sport Mode,

21:44.537 --> 21:46.873
which makes the exhaust
pop and bang.

21:49.376 --> 21:51.010
Woohoo! Mine!

21:56.383 --> 21:57.684
RICHARD: Oh, my God!

21:59.051 --> 22:00.920
Flat out, yeah.

22:03.089 --> 22:05.191
And it still grips!

22:05.257 --> 22:08.695
What is the point of traction
control on this thing?

22:08.761 --> 22:11.864
It's like putting a
nymphomania control on a nun.

22:22.709 --> 22:24.711
Oh, God!

22:38.525 --> 22:40.727
Where's he gone?

22:42.328 --> 22:45.432
How did he do that?
How did he get away from me

22:45.498 --> 22:48.267
in something
from the 18th century?

22:48.334 --> 22:49.902
Especially when I'm driving

22:49.969 --> 22:54.306
what is basically
a turbocharged barnacle.

22:54.441 --> 22:59.479
This has the most
sophisticated
four-wheel-drive system

22:59.546 --> 23:01.013
fitted to any car.

23:03.583 --> 23:06.619
Not even a Nissan GTR
could live with this.

23:11.357 --> 23:13.960
The Mustang, well,
that's for cruising down

23:14.026 --> 23:18.030
the Pacific Coast Highway,
listening to Don Henley.

23:18.097 --> 23:21.033
This is for storming up
the Stelvio Pass,

23:21.100 --> 23:22.735
listening to the Clash.

23:26.105 --> 23:29.909
But while it's a grippy,
technological masterpiece,

23:29.976 --> 23:35.381
it still has the blue-collar
character of its ancestors.

23:35.482 --> 23:40.720
In many ways, this reminds me
of the old Escort Cosworth,
and that was a great car.

23:40.787 --> 23:43.523
I actually had one in
the '90s. I called it Gary.

23:43.590 --> 23:47.994
It started every morning
and it always went,
"Do you want some?!"

23:48.060 --> 23:50.563
It was just
John Terry, really,
with windscreen wipers.

23:54.200 --> 23:56.703
RICHARD: Meanwhile,
having got rid of the ape,

23:56.769 --> 23:59.739
I was back on
my sightseeing tour.

23:59.806 --> 24:02.542
This is our Cheddar Gorge.

24:03.943 --> 24:06.613
Obviously it's not as big
as your gorge.

24:06.679 --> 24:08.515
The Grand Canyon is bigger.

24:08.581 --> 24:11.851
Well, it's longer
and deeper... and wider.

24:11.918 --> 24:14.554
Mm. But it doesn't have
any cheese in it.

24:14.621 --> 24:16.288
Why can't you
just leave me alone?

24:16.355 --> 24:19.258
I'm just saying, everything
in America comes with cheese,

24:19.325 --> 24:20.927
apart from the Grand Canyon.

24:20.993 --> 24:24.697
Whereas this canyon
does come with cheese,
and it's delicious.

24:24.764 --> 24:26.398
-Here, have some.
-I don't want cheese.

24:26.533 --> 24:29.001
-It's better than
Monterey Jack in a tube.
-You're ruining this!

24:29.068 --> 24:31.838
No, you are, because
you are telling everyone

24:31.904 --> 24:36.375
that the Mustang is better
than the Focus.

24:36.442 --> 24:38.277
-Well, it is.
-It isn't.

24:38.344 --> 24:41.013
-It is.
-No, it isn't.

24:41.080 --> 24:44.083
Look, I'm not saying this
is perfect, cos it isn't.

24:44.150 --> 24:47.319
There's a vertical choppiness
to the ride,
which is annoying.

24:47.386 --> 24:50.289
If you put your phone
in the phone holder
in front of the gear lever

24:50.356 --> 24:52.692
and then accelerate,
it shoots under the seat.

24:52.759 --> 24:53.893
You never see it again.

24:53.960 --> 24:55.862
Petrol tank, way too small.

24:55.928 --> 24:59.566
-And the styling is a bit...
yobbish.
!

24:59.566 --> 25:01.067
But, Hammond, look at this.

25:04.103 --> 25:05.938
Oh, yeah, you're right.

25:06.005 --> 25:09.876
Half a century of Mustang
history, heritage and pride,

25:09.942 --> 25:14.681
but it hasn't got a small
plastic strip on the door
in case you're a bit clumsy.

25:14.747 --> 25:18.317
No, it's brilliant, that.
And... this is faster.

25:18.384 --> 25:20.452
Well, no, it isn't.

25:20.587 --> 25:23.389
-It is.
-No, it isn't.

25:23.455 --> 25:25.925
-It is.
-It isn't.

25:25.992 --> 25:29.596
RICHARD: At this point,
I decided to abandon my tour

25:29.629 --> 25:32.599
and head for
the nearest airfield...

25:32.665 --> 25:34.667
...to teach Clarkson
a lesson.

25:39.906 --> 25:42.642
Right,
I've got 410 horsepower -

25:42.709 --> 25:44.310
that's 100 more than him.

25:44.376 --> 25:46.779
But there's something else
on here that's missing
on his Focus,

25:46.846 --> 25:49.148
and it's this - "line lock".

25:49.215 --> 25:52.484
So, engage it.
Press OK to initialise.

25:52.619 --> 25:54.787
"Initialising.
Initialising complete.

25:54.854 --> 25:56.889
Firmly apply and hold brake
to engage.

25:56.956 --> 25:59.358
Engaged. Press OK to begin."

26:01.828 --> 26:05.197
What that's doing
is locking the front brakes,

26:05.264 --> 26:08.034
so I can warm up my tyres.

26:08.100 --> 26:13.305
Hm. That is an ideal feature
for people who wake up
in the morning and think,

26:13.372 --> 26:16.175
"Do you know, I've got
too much tread on my tyres."

26:22.815 --> 26:25.184
Yeah!
I'm doing that automatically!

26:32.524 --> 26:34.961
What a moron.

26:35.027 --> 26:36.729
With my tyres warmed up,

26:36.796 --> 26:39.131
I took my place
on the start line.

26:42.802 --> 26:46.305
Right, race mode,
launch control,

26:46.372 --> 26:49.475
over-boost facility
on the turbocharger,

26:49.541 --> 26:54.546
four-wheel-drive,
and a man with lightning
reactions at the wheel.

26:54.681 --> 26:59.218
This car is going to
boing off the line
like a spring lamb.

27:01.320 --> 27:04.556
Launch control, first gear,
and we're ready to go.

27:22.608 --> 27:25.311
Oh, he's away first.

27:25.377 --> 27:28.280
The most incredible
launch control in the world!

27:30.482 --> 27:32.518
Come on!

27:32.584 --> 27:35.187
Come on, Jeremy.
Come on. You're winning.

27:36.723 --> 27:38.524
RICHARD: Oh, reeling him in!

27:46.198 --> 27:49.535
No, no, no!
That's simply impossible!

27:49.601 --> 27:51.738
Well, bless him for trying.

27:55.975 --> 27:59.345
Things I don't want to see
right now - number one, him.

27:59.411 --> 28:01.213
So er... I won, then.

28:01.280 --> 28:06.853
-Yes, but your car
doesn't have a drift button.

28:06.919 --> 28:08.220
-A drift button.

28:08.287 --> 28:09.889
Well, you push it,
and then,

28:09.956 --> 28:13.359
when you go round a corner,
the car drifts.

28:13.425 --> 28:14.626
-Yeah.

28:14.761 --> 28:16.628
You know, I'd love
to see that in action.

28:16.763 --> 28:18.430
-I'd love to see
you doing that.
-Yes.

28:18.497 --> 28:20.933
-I'll watch. Yeah, show me.
-You stay there.

28:21.000 --> 28:23.870
You will not... Even
James May could drift this.

28:23.936 --> 28:25.938
-Here we go!
-I can't wait to watch.

28:34.981 --> 28:37.149
JEREMY: Check it out,
ladies and gentlemen!

28:37.216 --> 28:38.785
Check it out!

28:38.785 --> 28:41.253
I'm drifting.

28:41.320 --> 28:44.190
What do you think of
that, Hammond? Look at that!

28:50.196 --> 28:51.798
Hammond?

28:54.166 --> 28:55.802
Hammond?

28:57.136 --> 28:58.504
Hammond!

29:06.045 --> 29:08.080
What?
You're not gonna blame me.

29:08.147 --> 29:11.984
-Well, I left you because
you were being moronic.

29:12.051 --> 29:13.652
-I wasn't!
-You were!

29:13.719 --> 29:14.987
Seriously,
who is going to buy

29:15.054 --> 29:16.823
a Ford Focus when,
for the same money,

29:16.856 --> 29:18.690
you could have
a V8

29:18.825 --> 29:20.159
-No-one.

29:20.226 --> 29:23.830
Nobody would. Mustang's
got so much more character.

29:23.863 --> 29:25.297
Hang on.
So, you agree with me?

29:25.364 --> 29:26.732
Oh, God, yes!
If I had the choice
of those two cars,

29:26.833 --> 29:29.468
I'd have the Mustang
every day of the week.

29:31.070 --> 29:33.840
So you ruined my day out
for no reason at all?

29:33.906 --> 29:38.177
I ruined your day out
because it was fun...
to ruin your day out.

29:38.244 --> 29:40.512
-Good work.
-It was good work.
Sorry about that.

29:40.579 --> 29:44.917
But anyway, we must now
find out how fast those Fords
go round our track,

29:44.984 --> 29:50.156
and that, of course, means
handing them over to our
other resident American -

29:50.222 --> 29:54.861
a man who thinks that shower
gel is basically communist.

29:54.861 --> 29:55.928
It's the American.

29:57.363 --> 29:59.598
JEREMY: There he is,
looking bewildered.

29:59.665 --> 30:01.400
And he's away!

30:03.169 --> 30:06.305
It sounds like a bunch
of goddamn mice in there.

30:09.375 --> 30:12.244
Why the hell don't they just
start with eight cylinders?

30:12.311 --> 30:17.449
Strangest mice I ever heard,
as he powers down the Isn't.

30:17.516 --> 30:19.351
That is a good noise.

30:19.418 --> 30:22.554
Arms working the wheel
like he's wrestling
a drifter,

30:22.621 --> 30:24.056
which, of course, he is.

30:24.123 --> 30:26.225
And already he's at
Your Name Here.

30:26.292 --> 30:29.028
Tyres squealing,
but it's clinging on well,

30:29.095 --> 30:31.230
and now the climb
back onto the Isn't.

30:31.297 --> 30:33.099
It ain't got no room in it.

30:34.233 --> 30:36.535
No place to put your beer.

30:36.602 --> 30:40.739
I think he and I
look for slightly different
things in a car.

30:40.806 --> 30:43.009
Anyway,
now hard on the brakes

30:43.075 --> 30:46.645
as he turns into
Old Lady's House.

30:46.712 --> 30:49.481
Yeah, he is dispatching that
with no dramas,

30:49.548 --> 30:51.550
and now he can get
the hammer down

30:51.617 --> 30:53.886
for the bumpy sprint
to Substation.

30:53.953 --> 30:55.421
Looking good.

30:55.487 --> 30:57.523
Four-wheel-drive cars can,
of course, understeer,

30:57.589 --> 31:00.859
but... nope,
not a whiff of it here.

31:00.927 --> 31:04.830
And Field Of Sheep,
tidy through there as well,

31:04.931 --> 31:06.398
and across the line.

31:07.666 --> 31:11.037
Now, I think
he might enjoy this one.

31:11.103 --> 31:13.605
And he is
wheel-spinning away!

31:14.941 --> 31:17.243
All right!
American muscle, baby!

31:18.410 --> 31:21.247
5.0 Mustang -
this thing is badass.

31:24.650 --> 31:27.386
It's got a trunk,
a place for my golf clubs.

31:27.453 --> 31:31.023
Pack up the old lady,
go for the weekend
somewhere in this thing,

31:31.090 --> 31:33.425
and you can haul ass
while you're goin'.

31:33.492 --> 31:37.163
Something there about an old
lady and hauling a bottom.

31:37.229 --> 31:38.430
Anyway, he's on the Isn't,

31:38.497 --> 31:41.033
and he's flying into
Your Name Here.

31:41.100 --> 31:44.370
The mighty Mustang has filled
the American with vigour,

31:44.436 --> 31:46.372
and he's being
surprisingly tidy.

31:49.976 --> 31:53.445
That's what us Americans
want, we want to
smoke the tyres.

31:53.512 --> 31:57.083
We want this thing
to just get shit and get.

31:57.149 --> 32:00.752
Literally no idea what he's
on about. It's just a noise.

32:00.819 --> 32:03.990
When this thing stops, man,
it stops on a dime.

32:03.990 --> 32:07.759
"It'll stop on a dime
and give you nine cents
change" is what we say.

32:07.826 --> 32:09.996
You really can't shut him up
about this one.

32:09.996 --> 32:13.665
Anyway, he is keeping it neat
round Old Lady's House,

32:13.732 --> 32:17.136
and then unleashing
that V8 fury

32:17.203 --> 32:19.671
over the rough stuff
to Substation.

32:19.738 --> 32:23.275
Hard on the brakes,
ready for the 90 left.

32:23.342 --> 32:25.444
Blip it up to Field Of Sheep.

32:25.511 --> 32:26.845
Here we go.

32:26.912 --> 32:31.017
Flurry of exuberance,
and across the line.

32:31.017 --> 32:32.684
-There we are.

32:35.787 --> 32:37.523
OK, here's the Lap Board.

32:37.589 --> 32:41.827
Let's have a look, first of
all, where the Focus went.

32:41.893 --> 32:43.595
So...

32:43.662 --> 32:45.064
Oh, there it is.

32:45.131 --> 32:47.533
Faster than an ST200 -
perhaps not surprising.

32:47.599 --> 32:48.500
Just as well.

32:48.567 --> 32:51.870
Now let's bring up
the Mustang.

32:51.937 --> 32:53.339
-Oh!

32:55.574 --> 32:58.444
-That's not embarrassing,
is it?

32:58.510 --> 33:02.514
The car that you, me,
and the American all prefer

33:02.581 --> 33:05.817
is quite a lot slower
than the European Focus.

33:05.884 --> 33:07.119
RICHARD: Yes.

33:07.186 --> 33:08.954
Anyway, listen,
let's move on, shall we,

33:09.055 --> 33:11.490
to Celebrity Brain Crash.

33:19.098 --> 33:20.866
Now...

33:20.932 --> 33:25.171
our guest this week
isn't just my favourite
Formula One driver,

33:25.237 --> 33:27.439
he's also a local boy.

33:27.506 --> 33:31.577
Oh, yeah, this is
the chatty man of motorsport,

33:31.643 --> 33:32.811
Mr Effervescent,

33:32.878 --> 33:35.547
ladies and gentlemen,
Kimi Räikkönen!

33:37.083 --> 33:38.484
Here he comes.

33:41.220 --> 33:42.954
RICHARD:
What are we gonna ask him?

33:43.089 --> 33:44.690
It doesn't matter
what you ask him.

33:44.756 --> 33:48.494
It doesn't, because you won't
get a coherent answer.

33:48.560 --> 33:50.429
Is he all right?

33:52.098 --> 33:53.365
JEREMY: No, hang on. Whoa!

33:54.500 --> 33:56.402
RICHARD: Oh, no.
JEREMY: Not again.

33:58.170 --> 34:00.506
No, he has, I'm afraid,
ladies and gentlemen,

34:00.572 --> 34:02.908
literally drunk himself
to death.

34:03.975 --> 34:05.411
JEREMY: Damn.

34:05.477 --> 34:08.114
-Does that mean
he's not coming on, then?

34:08.114 --> 34:09.315
Well, his liver has failed

34:09.381 --> 34:10.816
and he's now
slowly solidifying

34:10.882 --> 34:14.820
in the freezing dusk of an
Arctic night, so that's a no.

34:15.987 --> 34:17.256
Yeah, but it doesn't matter.

34:17.323 --> 34:19.258
Well, it does, cos I actually
rather liked Kimi.

34:19.325 --> 34:22.561
But I can think of something
else we can do to fill the time.

34:22.628 --> 34:25.131
Here's the thing.
Er... If you're watching this

34:25.197 --> 34:27.766
on the day the programme
is actually released,

34:27.833 --> 34:30.402
it is December 23rd.

34:30.469 --> 34:32.671
There are two days to go
until Christmas,

34:32.738 --> 34:37.176
and if you're a man,
you won't have done
any shopping yet.

34:38.744 --> 34:40.812
-But don't worry,
cos we've got your back.
-Oh, yeah.

34:40.879 --> 34:43.215
We have trawled the Internet
and the shops

34:43.282 --> 34:45.917
to find the best gift ideas.

34:45.984 --> 34:51.423
Yes, and here, in our special
Grand Tour Santa Land Grotto.

34:51.490 --> 34:53.492
-Yeah.

34:53.559 --> 34:55.894
Nice view. Nice everything.

34:55.961 --> 34:57.163
Yeah. Er...

34:57.229 --> 35:00.166
We begin with this
rather brilliant tray,

35:00.166 --> 35:04.203
which, apparently, is
the ideal place to put your
laptop or your breakfast.

35:04.270 --> 35:06.238
We have a picture of it
in action here.

35:08.474 --> 35:11.577
RICHARD: Hang on a minute!
-I see a couple of problems
with that.

35:11.643 --> 35:13.512
RICHARD: I can too.

35:13.579 --> 35:16.315
Well, now, the reason
I don't play chess any more

35:16.382 --> 35:19.050
is it's just so exhausting
to move the pieces around.

35:19.185 --> 35:22.421
-I know what you mean.
-Far too heavy, picking the
Queen up and moving her.

