decreed that they would be
back next year

50:38.136 --> 50:40.271
to take on Ferrari again.

50:40.338 --> 50:42.173
And to head up the campaign,

50:42.240 --> 50:45.576
he turned to
an American motorsport hero.

50:45.643 --> 50:48.879
My name's Carroll Shelby and
performance is my business.

50:48.946 --> 50:52.049
Shelby was a former
chicken farmer from Texas

50:52.117 --> 50:55.553
who took nitroglycerin pills
to keep his heart going.

50:55.620 --> 50:57.988
But he'd also racked up
countless victories

50:58.055 --> 51:00.525
as a driver and team owner.

51:00.591 --> 51:03.494
Given the task of turning
the GT40 into a winner,

51:03.561 --> 51:05.863
he put his top man
on the job.

51:05.930 --> 51:07.432
Coming up is Ken Miles,

51:07.498 --> 51:11.136
one of the best
sport-car drivers in America.

51:11.136 --> 51:15.606
Miles was a former
Second World War tank
commander from Birmingham -

51:15.673 --> 51:18.509
the one in England,
not Alabama.

51:18.576 --> 51:20.478
He was renowned
for speaking his mind

51:20.545 --> 51:23.648
and developing racing cars.

51:23.714 --> 51:25.416
Miles took the car
for a shakedown.

51:25.483 --> 51:28.719
Then he got out
and he told Shelby
and the Ford executives,

51:28.786 --> 51:30.388
"It's bloody awful!"

51:30.455 --> 51:32.157
Then he got to work,

51:32.190 --> 51:34.659
improving the brakes,
the engine,

51:34.725 --> 51:36.694
the aerodynamics,
the handling,

51:36.761 --> 51:41.766
and taming
the car's terrifying
high-speed instability.

51:41.832 --> 51:44.869
However, and even though he
and his team took amphetamine

51:44.935 --> 51:46.737
so that they could
stay awake all night,

51:46.804 --> 51:51.776
there simply wasn't time
to develop the car properly
for Le Mans.

51:51.842 --> 51:54.179
The GT40
may have been faster,

51:54.245 --> 51:56.314
but it was still fragile.

51:56.381 --> 51:58.183
At the 1965 race,

51:58.249 --> 52:00.751
six cars started,
none finished,

52:00.818 --> 52:04.722
and the Italians
humiliated Ford once again.

52:06.791 --> 52:09.727
So, untold millions
of dollars had been spent

52:09.794 --> 52:13.331
since the first GT40 emerged
from this building here,

52:13.398 --> 52:17.502
and yet not one car
had even finished the race.

52:17.568 --> 52:19.270
So Ford now faced
a difficult choice -

52:19.337 --> 52:23.374
he could throw in the towel
against Ferrari,
or he could fight on.

52:23.441 --> 52:26.611
What he actually did was
he had some business cards
printed,

52:26.677 --> 52:29.214
and he distributed them
to his Le Mans team.

52:29.247 --> 52:32.350
And on the cards it said,
"You'd better win."

52:32.417 --> 52:33.984
And so, a year later,

52:34.051 --> 52:36.687
the American giant
returned to Le Mans

52:36.754 --> 52:40.791
with its hopes
resting on this.

52:48.333 --> 52:49.800
OK, viewers,

52:49.867 --> 52:54.872
this is historic-race-car
bucket-list moment
number two,

52:54.939 --> 52:57.675
because this is
an actual GT40

52:57.742 --> 53:01.479
that competed at Le Mans
in 1966.

53:03.881 --> 53:07.252
All right, don't go mad, May,
it's worth 15-million quid.

53:08.653 --> 53:11.256
Sod it!
Let's make some noise!

53:17.728 --> 53:18.663
Oh, yes!

53:21.366 --> 53:22.967
In this new GT40,

53:23.033 --> 53:26.937
Ken Miles had racked up
thousands of test hours.

53:27.004 --> 53:30.475
Now the car was no longer
horribly unstable,

53:30.541 --> 53:34.879
but would sit rocksteady
at 210mph.

53:34.945 --> 53:39.884
And the Brummie tank
commander had the backing of
Ford's huge R&D department,

53:39.950 --> 53:42.653
who tackled the car's
appalling reliability.

53:44.889 --> 53:47.558
The brakes no longer went
into thermal shock

53:47.625 --> 53:49.960
at the end of
the long straight.

53:50.027 --> 53:53.898
The engine and transmission
were run on
a computerised test rig

53:53.964 --> 53:58.035
that simulated the whole of
the 24-Hour Le Mans race.

53:58.102 --> 54:00.671
Now, that's standard practice
in Formula One today,

54:00.738 --> 54:04.409
but in 1966
that was witchcraft.

54:06.411 --> 54:09.347
They weren't mucking about,
these blokes.

54:09.414 --> 54:12.049
But neither were
the opposition.

54:12.116 --> 54:15.320
Over in Italy, in response
to the new threat,

54:15.386 --> 54:17.755
Ferrari produced this.

54:24.228 --> 54:28.899
Called the P3,
it looked as sleek as a GT40.

54:28.966 --> 54:33.771
And at just 37.4 inches tall,
it was even lower.

54:38.443 --> 54:40.378
Avanti!

54:43.348 --> 54:45.650
Whoo! Holy mother!

54:45.716 --> 54:49.053
I best be a little bit
careful on this narrow road.

54:49.119 --> 54:51.856
It's worth £20 million.

54:53.824 --> 54:59.364
Where the GT40 boasted
a top speed of over 210mph,

54:59.397 --> 55:02.600
the P3 maxed out at just 190.

55:02.667 --> 55:08.773
But Enzo Ferrari was willing
to trade outright speed
for gains elsewhere.

55:10.040 --> 55:12.510
The Ferrari was lighter,
it was more agile.

55:12.577 --> 55:15.946
Ferrari reckoned
he could make up
the difference in the bends,

55:16.013 --> 55:19.384
and he wouldn't have to stop
so often for fuel.

55:20.985 --> 55:24.489
A David and Goliath battle
was looming.

55:24.555 --> 55:30.094
At the 1966 Le Mans race,
Ford arrived with an armada -

55:30.160 --> 55:33.398
eight cars,
20 tonnes of spares,

55:33.464 --> 55:35.800
and a squad
of world-class drivers,

55:35.866 --> 55:38.436
including Ken Miles himself.

55:38.503 --> 55:42.907
In comparison, Ferrari turned
up with just a trio of P3s,

55:42.973 --> 55:44.875
but Enzo had an ace
up his sleeve -

55:44.942 --> 55:48.613
the undisputed
fastest driver on the planet,

55:48.679 --> 55:53.183
Formula One World Champion
John Surtees.

55:53.250 --> 55:59.590
He came to me and said,
"John... we've got to beat
the Fords. Go out and do it."

55:59.657 --> 56:01.225
I thought
there was only one tactic -

56:01.291 --> 56:04.929
to have at least one car
be the hare.

56:04.995 --> 56:09.434
I said, "Look,
I don't mind being the hare."

56:09.434 --> 56:11.235
"The moment
that flag goes down,

56:11.301 --> 56:13.237
we need to be - bang - off,"

56:13.303 --> 56:18.108
tempting the Ford drivers
to perhaps overdrive
a little bit.

56:18.175 --> 56:21.111
If one could push them
hard enough for long enough,

56:21.178 --> 56:26.316
then there is more
likelihood, obviously,
of being able to break them.

56:26.451 --> 56:28.152
The plan was set.

56:28.218 --> 56:32.457
But, as zero hour approached,
everything unravelled.

56:32.523 --> 56:35.693
REPORTER: Shortly before
the race, we learned that
he wasn't going to drive,

56:35.760 --> 56:37.495
and we asked him about it.

56:37.562 --> 56:41.265
Yes, unfortunately
you've heard correct.
I won't be driving.

56:41.331 --> 56:43.333
REPORTER: What is the reason?

56:43.468 --> 56:46.471
Well, I suppose it's best
summed up at this stage

56:46.504 --> 56:49.006
by saying
"political reasons."

56:49.073 --> 56:51.341
JAMES: The problem was that
the Ferrari team manager

56:51.476 --> 56:53.744
was playing
his own political game.

56:53.811 --> 56:56.213
He had no particular liking
for Surtees,

56:56.280 --> 56:57.848
and he nominated
another driver

56:57.915 --> 57:00.951
to go out and start the race,
to be the hare,

57:01.018 --> 57:06.591
even though Surtees
was clearly
the fastest man available.

57:06.657 --> 57:11.195
SURTEES: And I just stormed
away, drove back, and
had it out with the old man.

57:11.261 --> 57:13.498
As the Italian papers put it,

57:13.531 --> 57:17.602
they showed a picture
of me walking out the gates
and saying,

57:17.668 --> 57:22.507
"The divorce of John Surtees
and Enzo."

57:24.675 --> 57:26.777
With Surtees out of the way,

57:26.844 --> 57:30.014
the Fords took the top four
slots in qualifying.

57:30.080 --> 57:34.519
And as the clock ticked down,
Henry Ford II
prepared to drop the flag,

57:34.585 --> 57:40.424
praying that, this time,
he would get his revenge.

57:40.525 --> 57:44.194
REPORTER:
Live from Le Mans, France,
it's the 24 Hours of Le Mans.

57:57.007 --> 57:59.544
At first, the Fords
stormed into the lead.

57:59.577 --> 58:01.411
But a few hours in,

58:01.546 --> 58:07.552
it was beginning to look like
a depressing repeat
of '64 and '65.

58:07.552 --> 58:10.387
As night fell, the Ferraris,
using their greater agility

58:10.454 --> 58:12.356
and their greater
fuel efficiency,

58:12.422 --> 58:14.458
were leading the race
one-two.

58:14.559 --> 58:20.565
Four of the eight GT40s were
out of the race altogether.

58:20.598 --> 58:25.603
Worse still, the Ford drivers
had strict orders
not to go balls-out

58:25.670 --> 58:29.073
for fear
of breaking the cars.

58:29.139 --> 58:32.209
But one man wasn't listening
to those orders.

58:32.276 --> 58:34.144
Ken Miles
put the hammer down,

58:34.211 --> 58:37.815
set blistering lap times,
and retook the lead for Ford.

58:39.349 --> 58:42.587
The Ferraris had no response
to this crushing pace,

58:42.587 --> 58:46.791
and by morning,
they had either
broken down or crashed.

58:48.626 --> 58:51.696
That afternoon, Henry Ford
watched his cars cruise home

58:51.762 --> 58:55.099
to a spectacular
one-two-three finish.

58:58.202 --> 59:02.272
REPORTER: First place
for the Ford GT Mk II,

59:02.339 --> 59:06.443
and a first-time win
for America at Le Mans.

59:06.510 --> 59:10.615
JAMES: Ford would go on
to win their next four
Le Mans races.

59:10.615 --> 59:13.784
But the man
who had contributed
so much to the team

59:13.851 --> 59:15.920
didn't get to see
these triumphs.

59:15.986 --> 59:19.624
Ken Miles was killed two
months after their first win,

59:19.657 --> 59:22.326
testing the latest GT40.

59:24.629 --> 59:28.232
It's impossible to calculate
how much Henry Ford spent

59:28.298 --> 59:30.901
on his three-year campaign
to break Ferrari,

59:30.968 --> 59:33.203
but experts reckon that,
at the very least,

59:33.270 --> 59:38.709
in today's money,
it was £360 million.

59:38.776 --> 59:42.647
Now, that's a big bill
for settling a spat
with an angry Italian.

59:44.649 --> 59:47.184
But look what
we got out of it -

59:47.251 --> 59:49.887
one of the world's
greatest cars.

59:56.927 --> 59:58.395
RICHARD: Very good.

59:58.462 --> 1:00:00.364
That was good. Very good.

1:00:07.037 --> 1:00:09.139
-I hate you.
-I know.

1:00:09.206 --> 1:00:14.144
No, but I really hate you
now, cos you've driven a
Ford GT40, and I never have.

1:00:14.211 --> 1:00:16.847
I mean, next week
are you gonna lick
Helena Christensen?

1:00:16.914 --> 1:00:18.382
-Look...

1:00:18.448 --> 1:00:21.819
I'm sure you could drive a
GT40 if you really wanted to.

1:00:21.886 --> 1:00:23.387
I can't, I'm too tall.

1:00:23.453 --> 1:00:25.289
Yeah, you mean fat.

1:00:34.799 --> 1:00:37.201
-Tall.

1:00:37.267 --> 1:00:39.036
Horizontally tall.

1:00:40.237 --> 1:00:42.439
Well, listen, whatever
dimension is the problem,

1:00:42.506 --> 1:00:44.041
I can't drive one.

1:00:44.108 --> 1:00:47.044
And on that terrible
disappointment,
it is time to end.

1:00:47.111 --> 1:00:49.613
Thank you so much
for watching. Good night.
